{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775849338679,"sessionID":"ses_28722a5a2ffeY5t3bH1W5LyxEo","part":{"id":"prt_d78ddd4e2001JBRsHTs7ajk0dP","messageID":"msg_d78ddb755001Gn2iJQ42MDnp3q","sessionID":"ses_28722a5a2ffeY5t3bH1W5LyxEo","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_901ea3fac2844f4a836c4dbd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Proposal: AR-011 — Router JWT 认证与签发\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication and token issuance capabilities in `pkg/router` to replace the current static bearer token authentication. This enables stateless authentication, token expiration, claims-based authorization, and integration with external identity providers.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nThe AR-010 router currently implements simple bearer token authentication where a static token is compared directly:\n\n```go\nif parts[1] != a.token {\n    http.Error(w, \"Unauthorized\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n    return\n}\n```\n\nThis approach has significant limitations:\n- **No token expiration**: Tokens remain valid indefinitely\n- **No cryptographically secure verification**: Simple string comparison\n- **No claims-based authorization**: Cannot extract user info or permissions\n- **No token revocation**: Cannot invalidate active tokens\n- **No token refresh**: Clients must re-authenticate with credentials\n- **No standard compliance**: Not compatible with OAuth2/OIDC flows\n\n### Goal\n\nImplement JWT-based authentication that:\n- Validates JWT tokens using cryptographic signatures (HMAC or RSA)\n- Supports token expiration and refresh\n- Extracts claims for authorization decisions\n- Provides token issuance endpoint for client authentication\n- Integrates with session management (AR-010) for seamless flow\n- Supports multiple signing algorithms (HS256, RS256)\n- Enables claims-based access control\n\n### Value\n- Stateless authentication at scale\n- Standard-compliant authentication (RFC 7519)\n- Fine-grained authorization via claims\n- Reduced database load (no session lookup)\n- Support for external identity providers\n- Improved security with short-lived tokens\n\n---\n\n## Scope\n\n### In-Scope\n\n| Deliverable | Description |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| JWT Validator | Validate JWT signatures, expiration, issuer, audience |\n| Token Claims | Extract and store user ID, roles, permissions from claims |\n| Token Issuer | Issue JWT tokens on successful authentication |\n| Token Refresh | Refresh expired tokens with valid refresh tokens |\n| Middleware Integration | Replace existing auth middleware with JWT validation |\n| Configuration | JWT secret, algorithms, expiration, issuer settings |\n| Metrics | Track token issuance, validation failures, expiration events |\n\n### Code Structure\n\n```\npkg/router/\n├── jwt/\n│   ├── validator.go          # JWT validation logic\n│   ├── claims.go             # Custom claims struct\n│   ├── issuer.go             # Token issuance\n│   ├── keys.go               # Key management\n│   └── config.go             # JWT configuration\n├── auth.go                   # Update to use JWT (existing)\n└── (existing files...)\n```\n\n### Configuration\n\nThe router supports these new JWT configuration options:\n\n| Option | Type | Default | Description |\n|--------|------|---------|-------------|\n| JWTEnabled | bool | false | Enable JWT authentication |\n| JWTSecretKey | string | \"\" | Secret key for HS256 signing |\n| JWTPublicKeyFile | string | \"\" | Public key file for RS256 |\n| JWTPrivateKeyFile | string | \"\" | Private key file for RS256 |\n| JWTAlgorithm | string | \"HS256 | Signing algorithm (HS256, RS256, ES256) |\n| JWTIssuer | string | \"agentcube\" | Token issuer claim |\n| JWTAudience | []string | [] | Expected audience claims |\n| JWTAccessTokenTTL | duration | 15m | Access token time-to-live |\n| JWTRefreshTokenTTL | duration | 24h | Refresh token time-to-live |\n| JWTIssuerEndpoint | string | \"/auth/token\" | Token issuance endpoint |\n| JWTValidateOnStart | bool | true | Validate keys on startup |\n\n### Out-of-Scope\n- OIDC provider integration — future enhancement\n- Distributed JWT validation (shared keys) — future enhancement\n- Token blacklisting/revocation list — future enhancement\n- Multi-tenant JWT claims — future enhancement\n\n---\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n|------------|--------|---------|\n| github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5 | ^5.2 | JWT parsing and validation |\n| github.com/google/uuid | ^1.6 | Token ID generation |\n| github.com/volcano/sh/agentcube/pkg/router | local | Existing router module |\n\n### Upstream Dependencies\n\n- **AR-010 Session Management** — JWT tokens integrate with session store\n- **AR-009 Router Core** — Provides the reverse proxy foundation\n\n### Downstream Consumers\n\n1. **External Clients** — Obtain and use JWT tokens for API access\n2. **Backend Services** — Validate JWT claims from router\n3. **Monitoring Systems** — JWT metrics for security auditing\n\n### Risks\n\n| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|------------|\n| Key leakage | High | Use secure key storage, rotate regularly |\n| Algorithm confusion | High | Explicitly specify allowed algorithms |\n| Token forgery | High | Verify signatures with trusted keys |\n| Clock skew | Medium | Use leeway for expiration checks |\n| Large claims | Medium | Limit claim size, validate upfront |\n\n---\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Option 1: JWT with Symmetric Keys (HS256) (Selected)\n\n**Approach**: Use a shared secret key for signing and validating JWT tokens.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Simple implementation\n- Low computational overhead\n- Easy key rotation\n- No external dependencies\n\n**Cons**:\n- Key must be shared between all instances\n- Key distribution challenge in multi-instance deployments\n\n**Decision**: Selected — provides the best balance of simplicity and security for initial implementation.\n\n---\n\n### Option 2: JWT with Asymmetric Keys (RS256)\n\n**Approach**: Use RSA key pair for signing (private key) and validation (public key).\n\n**Pros**:\n- Private key never leaves the issuer\n- Public key can be distributed freely\n- Better for distributed systems\n\n**Cons**:\n- More complex key management\n- Higher computational overhead\n- Larger token size\n\n**Decision**: Supported as configuration option for production deployments requiring key separation.\n\n---\n\n### Option 3: OAuth2/OIDC Integration\n\n**Approach**: Delegate authentication to external OAuth2 provider.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Industry standard\n- Social login support\n- Built-in MFA\n- Centralized user management\n\n**Cons**:\n- External dependency on identity provider\n- Network latency for validation\n- Complex setup\n- Not suitable for all deployments\n\n**Decision**: Deferred — valuable for enterprise deployments but adds significant complexity.\n\n---\n\n### Option 4: PASETO (Platform-Agnostic Security Tokens)\n\n**Approach**: Use PASETO instead of JWT.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Simplified security model\n- Explicit version header\n- No algorithm confusion attacks\n\n**Cons**:\n- Less ecosystem support\n- Fewer client libraries\n- Newer standard\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — JWT has broader ecosystem support and sufficient security for current use cases.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: JWT Core\n- [ ] Define JWT configuration struct\n- [ ] Implement key loading (secret file, RSA key files)\n- [ ] Create Claims struct with standard + custom claims\n- [ ] Implement JWT validator with signature verification\n- [ ] Add expiration and claims validation\n\n### Phase 2: Token Issuance\n- [ ] Implement token issuer with access/refresh tokens\n- [ ] Add token endpoint handler (/auth/token)\n- [ ] Support username/password authentication\n- [ ] Implement token refresh endpoint\n- [ ] Add token revocation (optional)\n\n### Phase 3: Middleware Integration\n- [ ] Update Authenticator to use JWT validator\n- [ ] Extract claims and store in request context\n- [ ] Add claims-based authorization middleware\n- [ ] Support Authorization: Bearer <token> format\n\n### Phase 4: Session Integration\n- [ ] Link JWT claims with session management (AR-010)\n- [ ] Store user ID from JWT in session\n- [ ] Enable session creation on JWT validation\n- [ ] Handle token refresh with session update\n\n### Phase 5: Metrics and Observability\n- [ ] Track JWT validation attempts (success/failure)\n- [ ] Track token issuance counts\n- [ ] Track token expiration events\n- [ ] Add JWT-specific error logging\n\n### Phase 6: Testing\n- [ ] Unit tests for JWT validation\n- [ ] Unit tests for token issuance\n- [ ] Unit tests for middleware\n- [ ] Integration tests with various algorithms\n- [ ] Key rotation tests\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] JWT tokens are validated using configured algorithm\n- [ ] Expired tokens are rejected with 401 status\n- [ ] Invalid signatures are rejected with 401 status\n- [ ] Token endpoint issues access and refresh tokens\n- [ ] Refresh endpoint issues new access tokens\n- [ ] Claims are extracted and available in request context\n- [ ] JWT middleware integrates with existing auth infrastructure\n- [ ] Configuration supports both HS256 and RS256\n- [ ] JWT metrics are exported (jwt_validated_total, jwt_issued_total, jwt_validation_errors_total)\n- [ ] Unit tests pass with >70% coverage\n- [ ] Graceful handling of key rotation","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/client/informers/externalversions/runtime/v1alpha1/interface.go\">\nERROR [4:2] \"github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1\" imported and not used\n</diagnostics>\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/w